DataScienceIdentityFreeForm: Systems Engineers/Master Schedulers/Cost-estimators/Six-sigma professionals with years of experience regard the depth of knowledge and experience of anyone who advertises a "PMP" certificate similarly as to how I perceive many self-declared "Data Scientists."  IMHO, most modern data science tools (e.g. Spotfire, Hadoop, etc.) are best leveraged by those who have pushed limits of more common data tools (e.g. Excel), wrangled cumbersome datasets, have experienced first hand data pitfalls (e.g. variable definitions, formats, relational calculus/algebra mistakes, etc.), understand the fine balance of computational and time constraints versus data needs, etc. The level of inefficiency and sheer quantity of serious mistakes I have personally discovered (and helped remedy) by "Data Scientists" within treasury, audit teams, analytics teams, etc. at the biggest financial institutions on the planet is astounding...

DataScienceIdentityFreeForm: I think that 'data scientist' is a misleading industry role label. The current scientific method in natural sciences is not an inductive one (see Paul Hoyningen Huene); although, most of what is done in industry is basically model induction, the standard scientific method in the 18th century. Besides that, the responsibility associated to the 'data scientist' role is not new. It visits us from time to time, like waves: from no structure to relational databases, from databases to data warehouses, and now from data to prediction. The promise has been the same: past data will lead us to a better future. And the threat is also the same: the future may not repeat the past.

PersonalProjectsChallengeFreeForm: For me right now it is determining what and how to deal with columns that have sparse data.  In some cases you could just omit that data from all analysis, but that is definitely not the best way to do it all the time.  Then it depends on the data; if it is a time series, do you interpolate, or just carry forward the last known value, or something else?  You need to make sure there is a good justification for what you do, and that you understand how it may impact the results of the analysis.

InterestingProblemFreeForm: Urban Air QualityDenver (where I currently live) has air quality testing stations set up around the city which use IR spectrometers (or similar?) to measure the emissions (NOx, CO, unburned HC) of vehicles driving past them. This could very easily be taken to the next level using 1. cameras to photograph the license plates of vehicles which do not meet emissions standards and 2. an automated system (based on machine learning and a couple simple databases) to flag offenders and require them to bring their vehicle in for inspection. If a vehicle passes, no need to bring it in for emissions testing (currently Denver residents are required to get an emissions test at a 3rd party testing station every 2 years and waste half a day at the DMV renewing vehicle registration therewith). It would both eliminate unnecessary bureaucracy (since most vehicles are already emissions compliant) and improve air quality (since offenders would be identified more quickly than every 2 years).

The benchmark providers have implicit assumptions about the test condition. This makes many public tests poorly applicable to our own approach. We bootstrap models from a sparse-label start vs curated data where all labels are known. The criteria for success are different in harvesting. The optimalities are not identical, even for small task variations. Therefore I get tired of the requirement to use common benchmark data (reviewers!), that does not allow us to expose the value of our new methods. We know by now that Deep Learning) works well: I am not interested in small deltas on the performance, we need fundamental guidelines for model design. It is all supposed to be machine intelligence but in actuality ML/DS still involves a huge amount of expensive human labor.

ImpactfulAlgorithmFreeForm: All of the algorithms I have worked with into a complete usable form have been for purely academic purposes, and all purposed for use with stock/futures market data to build a right return portfolio, while still trying to keep risk low.  That being said it would have to be a nearest neighbors algorithm I built to be extremely scale-able.  Since it was working with time series data, I was allowing it to use a period of history to check for "similarities" in the price/return trends for a set of stocks, not just the prices/returns for the portfolio on one day.  It was only setup to have a number passed, not a formula, if you wanted the time range to change as the algorithm increased the history it had to look at.  It also let you choose how to weight each progressive day back that you had it look at in the history.  The options included uniform, exponential decay, and geometric decay.  Then it also allowed you to choose how the "near-ness" of each of the data points was calculated, some of the options were absolute difference, Newtonian distance, and a few others.
